Doc Del,<br><br>
Your response to my reposted question was, as usual, piercingly analytical. We are on similar wavelengths. However, it is important in my exploration of things that I understand the motivations of the protestors. That is why I formulated the question the way I did. I still have memories chasing me that are still unresolved. I may be a dreamer to think I would hear from those in the protestor ranks who abused returning Vietnam Veterans. Perhaps their silence is the answer I seek.<br><br>
Nurse Ratchet,<br><br>
We have not yet conversed. I found one of your comments interesting:<br><br>
&quot;Some things that amaze me as I've read 100's of these posts are how s-o-m-e vets *still* (1) blame protesters for our &quot;defeat,&quot;&quot;<br><br>
It is my feeling that the Vietnam War was &quot;lost&quot; long before we were involved in that countries problems. It has been expressed to me that in the waining days of WW2, our continued support of French colonialism via the policy of Harry Truman really cast the die. It has also been said to me that the Vietnam War was the last battle of WW2. Since you are a more avid historian than I, I would appreciate your thoughts on these ideas. They are provocative, but may be a good bracket around the truth.<br><br>
As far as the protestors are concerned, I know many of them give their movement credit for stopping the war. I think the war just ran out of political steam as a natural course of anything that is ill conceived and then horribly and incompetantly excecuted to boot.  <br><br>
Regards to you both,<br><br>
Arthur Varanelli
